[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Analyzing class accessibility rules**\n\nI'm thinking about the rule for naming test classes related to anonymous classes and whether helper classes are concerned here. Using anonymous classes might make them non-public. However, in Scala 3, local classes can essentially compile to a public final class even if they're conceptually local. I'm recalling that Java's local class access flags show different modifiers, and I wonder if Scala treats public visibility differently. I might need to create a Java file to be thorough, but I'm also considering nested definitions in Scala.\n\n**Defining class access levels**\n\nI’m considering test classes, noting they are all public. I can define helper classes as private nested within a public test class. In Scala, a private final class compiles as an inner class, which raises questions about access flags. I think nested classes might have private access, which reflects in their modifiers. So, I’ll implement a Java-like private inner class to instantiate within the test, but I’m wondering if its runtime class will reflect as public or not.\n\n**Confirming method access**\n\nI’m considering whether it returns public methods regardless of class, and I think it does include the public methods of private classes too, similar to how it worked before at the top level. That seems to affirm my initial thought. It's good news if that's the case! It feels reassuring to know that I’ve got this understanding correct. Now I can confidently move forward with that information.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_077223540226434e016a29abe7447881978d078cc0e49d8df4\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqKav9GQo8wkMRX1k-Myjgib9UFho4hCNct2wEdugV-PFZulVofFIJPUJ-yxhJvpZoQOjEZPnS1CgiwSTjDr3dnxcYlfLCH-1sZJG93SQc48_cto1FPSdDLenNR2DFck0pZ3svwvRC-rTyFWOEm8An94vktP5dS4ch0q9T5pod8U3zMlEIrpsDWigE7EpvxGmrWJ2lIO9LZFGL8y